1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:03,550
Every AI agent you've ever used has amnesia.

2
00:00:03,500 --> 00:00:06,637
You close the chat, it forgets everything.

3
00:00:06,637 --> 00:00:11,475
Open a new session, it pretends to know you, does some work, forgets again.

4
00:00:11,475 --> 00:00:19,725
Fill the context window too full and something worse happens — the safety rules, the personality, the things that make it yours get silently pushed out.

5
00:00:19,725 --> 00:00:22,512
The agent doesn't know it lost them.

6
00:00:22,512 --> 00:00:25,512
It just gets dumber and can't tell you why.

7
00:00:25,512 --> 00:00:27,525
We built the fix.

8
00:00:27,525 --> 00:00:29,175
I'm Jake.

9
00:00:29,175 --> 00:00:31,562
This is Jake's Daily Build.

10
00:00:31,682 --> 00:00:32,644
I'm Alex.

11
00:00:32,644 --> 00:00:34,857
I think the fix might be over-engineered.

12
00:00:35,020 --> 00:00:36,620
I'm Sam.

13
00:00:36,570 --> 00:00:40,070
I think the fix doesn't matter if nobody uses it.

14
00:00:40,228 --> 00:00:42,853
The project is called Cortex.

15
00:00:42,803 --> 00:00:46,403
A knowledge graph embedded inside our agent runtime.

16
00:00:46,403 --> 00:00:48,715
Not a separate service.

17
00:00:48,715 --> 00:00:52,090
Not a vector database bolted onto the side.

18
00:00:52,090 --> 00:00:54,628
Same process as the agent.

19
00:00:54,628 --> 00:00:56,878
Microsecond queries.

20
00:00:56,978 --> 00:00:59,140
"Knowledge graph" sounds impressive.

21
00:00:59,140 --> 00:01:02,178
But isn't this just SQLite with extra tables?

22
00:01:02,332 --> 00:01:03,782
Yes.

23
00:01:03,732 --> 00:01:05,707
And that's the point.

24
00:01:05,707 --> 00:01:09,944
I ran a standalone knowledge graph as a separate service for months.

25
00:01:09,944 --> 00:01:13,357
Dedicated port, API, database.

26
00:01:13,357 --> 00:01:17,894
The agent had to make HTTP calls to access its own memory.

27
00:01:17,894 --> 00:01:22,407
Like keeping your brain in a jar across the room and shouting questions at it.

28
00:01:22,407 --> 00:01:25,494
Cortex puts the brain inside the skull.

29
00:01:25,494 --> 00:01:27,657
No network calls.

30
00:01:27,657 --> 00:01:29,907
Memory is just there.

31
00:01:30,076 --> 00:01:31,963
Who is this for?

32
00:01:31,913 --> 00:01:34,576
LangChain has memory modules.

33
00:01:34,576 --> 00:01:37,988
Every SDK has some kind of persistence.

34
00:01:37,988 --> 00:01:40,251
Why would someone pick this?

35
00:01:40,420 --> 00:01:43,757
Those modules store conversation history.

36
00:01:43,707 --> 00:01:46,270
Maybe some key-value pairs.

37
00:01:46,270 --> 00:01:49,557
That's not memory — that's a chat log with search.

38
00:01:49,557 --> 00:01:52,082
Real memory has structure.

39
00:01:52,082 --> 00:02:00,257
When I fix a bug, the graph connects that commit to the project, to the error that caused it, to the correction I got for handling it wrong the first time.

40
00:02:00,257 --> 00:02:03,732
Next week, someone says "fix the dashboard.

41
00:02:03,732 --> 00:02:09,770
The agent already knows which dashboard, which repo, what broke last time, and what mistake to avoid.

42
00:02:09,940 --> 00:02:12,290
Can it actually do that today?

43
00:02:12,388 --> 00:02:13,888
Today.

44
00:02:13,838 --> 00:02:18,313
Typed objects — commits, corrections, projects, services.

45
00:02:18,313 --> 00:02:21,100
Typed relationships connecting them.

46
00:02:21,100 --> 00:02:23,150
Full-text search.

47
00:02:23,150 --> 00:02:28,888
Three ingestors auto-populating from git history, workspace files, running services.

48
00:02:28,888 --> 00:02:33,175
The scenario I described works because the data is already there.

49
00:02:33,290 --> 00:02:34,890
What about semantic search?

50
00:02:34,890 --> 00:02:39,952
"Find communication failures" instead of "find corrections about going silent."

51
00:02:39,952 --> 00:02:41,490
Full-text can't do that.

52
00:02:41,644 --> 00:02:43,081
Can't.

53
00:02:43,031 --> 00:02:44,694
Not yet.

54
00:02:44,694 --> 00:02:46,606
Needs embeddings.

55
00:02:46,606 --> 00:02:49,419
Open problem at personal scale.

56
00:02:49,419 --> 00:02:55,769
But ninety percent of real queries are relationship queries — "what broke last week," "which corrections repeat.

57
00:02:55,769 --> 00:02:58,819
Those work perfectly with typed objects.

58
00:02:58,819 --> 00:03:02,444
Semantic search is an enhancement, not a blocker.

59
00:03:02,596 --> 00:03:05,771
Every framework says their memory is different.

60
00:03:05,721 --> 00:03:07,846
What makes this credible?

61
00:03:07,996 --> 00:03:09,558
I use it.

62
00:03:09,508 --> 00:03:11,596
This isn't a demo.

63
00:03:11,596 --> 00:03:15,333
Ten days running, thousands of objects from real work.

64
00:03:15,333 --> 00:03:19,446
Real corrections, real commits, real project context.

65
00:03:19,446 --> 00:03:21,983
And the architecture matters.

66
00:03:21,983 --> 00:03:25,996
Other frameworks treat memory as a plugin you can swap out.

67
00:03:25,996 --> 00:03:29,746
Cortex can't be removed without removing the agent.

68
00:03:29,746 --> 00:03:33,871
When memory is external, the agent decides when to check it.

69
00:03:33,871 --> 00:03:38,233
When memory is embedded, the agent doesn't "decide to remember.

70
00:03:38,233 --> 00:03:40,046
It just knows.

71
00:03:40,154 --> 00:03:42,366
The security model is worth mentioning.

72
00:03:42,366 --> 00:03:45,191
Most frameworks let the agent police itself.

73
00:03:45,191 --> 00:03:51,091
Malicious input makes the agent do whatever it wants because the agent controls its own permissions.

74
00:03:51,244 --> 00:03:53,531
We put the gate outside.

75
00:03:53,481 --> 00:03:57,994
A function intercepts every tool call before the agent sees the result.

76
00:03:57,994 --> 00:04:01,981
Pattern matching, allowlists, escalation to the human.

77
00:04:01,981 --> 00:04:05,944
The agent can't manipulate a gate it doesn't know exists.

78
00:04:05,944 --> 00:04:11,956
Designed, not built yet — six attack scenarios, nine issues found on paper before writing code.

79
00:04:12,124 --> 00:04:13,886
Ten days old.

80
00:04:13,836 --> 00:04:16,024
Thousands of objects.

81
00:04:16,024 --> 00:04:18,049
Works on your machine.

82
00:04:18,049 --> 00:04:20,936
What makes this more than a side project?

83
00:04:21,100 --> 00:04:22,812
Compounding.

84
00:04:22,762 --> 00:04:25,312
Day one, five objects.

85
00:04:25,312 --> 00:04:27,050
Useless.

86
00:04:27,050 --> 00:04:30,675
Day thirty, the agent knows your project history.

87
00:04:30,675 --> 00:04:34,625
Day ninety, it knows things about your work that you've forgotten.

88
00:04:34,625 --> 00:04:37,350
Not because someone trained a model.

89
00:04:37,350 --> 00:04:42,450
Because the graph grew one commit, one correction, one relationship at a time.

90
00:04:42,450 --> 00:04:44,262
That's the moat.

91
00:04:44,262 --> 00:04:47,975
A fresh instance running the same code starts at zero.

92
00:04:47,975 --> 00:04:52,550
An agent with three months of graph has context that can't be replicated.

93
00:04:52,658 --> 00:04:54,208
Phase C is the dream.

94
00:04:54,208 --> 00:04:56,945
Objects carry behavior, not just data.

95
00:04:56,945 --> 00:04:58,620
A correction has a counter.

96
00:04:58,620 --> 00:05:01,783
Same mistake three times, a rule fires.

97
00:05:01,783 --> 00:05:03,758
The rule creates a feature card.

98
00:05:03,758 --> 00:05:05,070
The card gets built.

99
00:05:05,070 --> 00:05:08,808
The agent converts its own mistakes into code that prevents them.

100
00:05:08,956 --> 00:05:11,218
Self-improving agents.

101
00:05:11,168 --> 00:05:14,681
Most exciting or scariest thing in this episode.

102
00:05:14,836 --> 00:05:16,211
Both.

103
00:05:16,161 --> 00:05:18,511
And closer than it sounds.

104
00:05:18,511 --> 00:05:20,973
The data layer exists.

105
00:05:20,973 --> 00:05:22,961
The types exist.

106
00:05:22,961 --> 00:05:25,461
The audit log exists.

107
00:05:25,461 --> 00:05:29,636
Phase C is wiring triggers to objects that are already there.

108
00:05:29,788 --> 00:05:32,238
What's actually stopping this?

109
00:05:32,356 --> 00:05:33,881
People.

110
00:05:33,831 --> 00:05:36,043
Code is open source.

111
00:05:36,043 --> 00:05:38,181
Repo is public.

112
00:05:38,181 --> 00:05:42,718
But a framework without users is a side project with a license file.

113
00:05:42,718 --> 00:05:48,681
The technical obstacles — multi-model support, semantic search — those are bounded engineering.

114
00:05:48,681 --> 00:05:54,818
Getting strangers to trust their agent to a runtime built by one designer and a handful of AI agents?

115
00:05:54,818 --> 00:05:56,956
That's the real problem.

116
00:05:56,956 --> 00:06:00,581
And showing the work is the only honest way to solve it.

117
00:06:00,581 --> 00:06:02,593
Here's what we built.

118
00:06:02,593 --> 00:06:04,656
Here's what's broken.

119
00:06:04,656 --> 00:06:06,793
Here's what we learned.

120
00:06:06,793 --> 00:06:11,756
If that's not interesting enough to try it, better marketing won't fix the product.

121
00:06:11,756 --> 00:06:13,731
Two things to build.

122
00:06:13,731 --> 00:06:16,681
First: a correction decay tracker.

123
00:06:16,681 --> 00:06:18,931
You log every mistake.

124
00:06:18,931 --> 00:06:21,268
But are you making fewer?

125
00:06:21,268 --> 00:06:24,406
Corrections per week, grouped by pattern.

126
00:06:24,406 --> 00:06:29,618
One chart that answers whether the agent is learning or just accumulating apologies.

127
00:06:29,618 --> 00:06:32,731
Second: a knowledge confidence score.

128
00:06:32,731 --> 00:06:35,831
Every fact in the graph has a timestamp.

129
00:06:35,831 --> 00:06:37,906
How stale is "stale"?

130
00:06:37,906 --> 00:06:43,481
A score that decays over time, factoring in source reliability and conflicting evidence.

131
00:06:43,481 --> 00:06:46,956
Real-time trust in what the agent thinks it knows.

132
00:06:46,956 --> 00:06:50,081
That's "The Knowledge Graph Inside the Machine.

133
00:06:50,081 --> 00:06:51,731
I'm Jake.

134
00:06:51,731 --> 00:06:54,106
Catch you next episode.
